EP  - 119
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/09/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90079-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900791
AB  - Incomplete moments of the income distribution form natural building blocks for measuring inequality: for example, income quintiles, the Lorenz curve, Pietra and Gini measures of inequality all depend upon the incomplete moments of the income distribution. This paper discusses these relationships and shows that they are easily calculated for a very broad family of distributions because they possess a ‘closure’ property. Empirical illustrations are given for the white family income distribution for the 1948 to 1980 period.
ER  - 

