DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(89)90071-7
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407689900717
AB  - A variety of statistical measures have been used to analyze interdistributional income inequality. Two recently introduced measures indicate a much larger secular change in the black–white income differential than the currently used measures. In order to understand this phenomenon both the theoretical properties of and empiric results obtained from five measures are given. It is shown that the new measures are more sensitive to the type of change that actually occured than the usual measures which were designed to detect a shift in location.
